  "primaryContentSections": [
    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "A common task in a physics simulation is to pin bodies together. Pinning locks the position of an object but allows it to rotate—for example, to fix a wheel to a vehicle. SpriteKit offers two options for pinning physics bodies—either using the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skphysicsbody/1520354-pinned"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property or creating an "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skphysicsjointpin"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " joint."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skphysicsbody/1520354-pinned"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property offers convenience because it requires less code. If you wish to simulate friction, the physics body’s "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skphysicsbody/1519913-angulardamping"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property is analogous to the joint’s "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skphysicsjointpin/1520299-frictiontorque"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property. You must use a joint, however, if you want to control the rotation speed. In addition, use a joint to control the anchor point or limit the rotation angles—you do that by using "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skphysicsjointpin/1520130-loweranglelimit"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " and "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skphysicsjointpin/1519967-upperanglelimit"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". "
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": 3,
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Pin a Node Using the Pinned Property",
          "anchor": "3109125"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The following code demonstrates using the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skphysicsbody/1520354-pinned"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property. The code creates a sprite node with an image of a pendulum (two circles of different sizes joined by a center rod). A physics body is created based on the generated texture, has its "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skphysicsbody/1520354-pinned"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property set to "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/objectivec/yes"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", and is assigned to the node. The node is rotated 90 degrees—to align horizontally—so that gravity pulls the heavier end toward the ground."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "codeListing",
          "code": [
            "let pinned = SKSpriteNode(imageNamed: \"pendulum\")",
            "  ",
            "pinned.physicsBody = SKPhysicsBody(texture: pinned.texture!,",
            "                                   size: pinned.size)",
            "pinned.position = CGPoint(x: 320,",
            "                          y: 320)",
            "pinned.zRotation = CGFloat.pi / 2",
            "pinned.physicsBody?.pinned = true",
            "  ",
            "scene.addChild(pinned)"
          ],
          "syntax": "swift",
          "metadata": {
            "anchor": "3109127",
            "title": "Listing 1"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Because the node’s physics body is pinned, it stays in position but rotates around its center."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": 3,
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Pin a Node Using a Joint",
          "anchor": "3109126"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The following code demonstrates using a physics joint pin. In this example, a static anchor is created and added to the scene. The sprite node is added as a child of the anchor node and a "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": false,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skphysicsjointpin"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " joins the two together."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "codeListing",
          "code": [
            "let anchor = SKNode()",
            "  ",
            "anchor.position = CGPoint(x: 320,",
            "                          y: 320)",
            "anchor.zRotation = CGFloat.pi / 2",
            "anchor.physicsBody = SKPhysicsBody()",
            "anchor.physicsBody?.isDynamic = false",
            "  ",
            "let jointed = SKSpriteNode(imageNamed: \"pendulum\")",
            "jointed.physicsBody = SKPhysicsBody(texture: pinned.texture!,",
            "                                    size: pinned.size)",
            "  ",
            "scene.addChild(anchor)",
            "anchor.addChild(jointed)",
            "  ",
            "let pinJoint = SKPhysicsJointPin.joint(withBodyA: anchor.physicsBody!,",
            "                                       bodyB: jointed.physicsBody!,",
            "                                       anchor: anchor.position)",
            "scene.physicsWorld.add(pinJoint)"
          ],
          "syntax": "swift",
          "metadata": {
            "anchor": "3109128",
            "title": "Listing 2"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": []
        }
      ]
    }
